      "by\n  refine' lt_of_le_of_ne (refinement_le B hB hB' hB'') _\n  intro h\n  have h₁ : ∃ (N : PersistenceSubmodule M) (hN : N ∈ D), B N hN ≠ {N} := H\n  obtain ⟨N, hN, hB_ne⟩ := h₁\n  have h₂ : B N hN ≠ {N} := hB_ne\n  have h₃ : B N hN ≠ {N} := hB_ne\n  have h₄ : (refinement B hB hB' hB'').carrier = ⋃ N, ⋃ hN, B N hN := rfl\n  have h₅ : D.carrier = D := rfl\n  have h₆ : (refinement B hB hB' hB'').carrier = D.carrier := by\n    simpa [h₄, h₅] using h\n  have h₇ : N ∈ D := hN\n  have h₈ : B N hN ⊆ (⋃ N, ⋃ hN, B N hN) := by\n    intro x hx\n    exact Set.mem_iUnion.mpr ⟨N, Set.mem_iUnion.mpr ⟨hN, hx⟩⟩\n  have h₉ : ∃ (x : B N hN), x ≠ N := by\n    by_contra! h₉\n    have h₁₀ : B N hN = {N} := by\n      apply Set.eq_singleton_iff_unique_mem.mpr\n      constructor\n      · by_cases h₁₁ : N ∈ B N hN\n        · exact h₁₁\n        · exfalso\n          have h₁₂ : ∃ (x : B N hN), x ≠ N := by\n            use ⟨N, by simp_all [Set.mem_iUnion]⟩\n            <;> simp_all [Set.mem_iUnion]\n          simp_all [Set.mem_iUnion]\n      · intro y hy\n        have h₁₁ := h₉ ⟨y, hy⟩\n        simp_all\n    contradiction\n  obtain ⟨⟨x, hx⟩, hx_ne⟩ := h₉\n  have h₁₀ : x ∈ (⋃ N, ⋃ hN, B N hN) := by\n    exact Set.mem_iUnion.mpr ⟨N, Set.mem_iUnion.mpr ⟨hN, hx⟩⟩\n  have h₁₁ : x ∈ D.carrier := by\n    rw [h₆] at h₁₀\n    exact h₁₀\n  have h₁₂ : x ∈ D := h₁₁\n  have h₁₃ : x = x := rfl\n  simp_all [Set.mem_iUnion, Set.mem_singleton_iff]\n  <;>\n    (try contradiction) <;>\n    (try\n      {\n        aesop\n      })\n  <;>\n    (try simp_all [Set.mem_iUnion, Set.mem_singleton_iff]) <;>\n    (try\n      {\n        exfalso\n        aesop\n      })",
      "∃ N, ∃ (hN : N ∈ D), B N hN ≠ {N}` gives us such a potential candidate `N`.\n4. However, the current approach to `refinement_lt_of_exists_ne_singleton` does not fully use the hypothesis `H` and instead relies on a missing step involving sSup comparisons, which is currently marked with `sorry`.\n\nThe issue is that:\n- The refinement `D' = refinement B hB hB' hB''` is defined as the union over all `N ∈ D` of the sets `B N hN`. \n- For any `N ∈ D`, we have `N = sSup (B N hN)` by `hB`, and `B N hN` is independent by `hB'`.\n- The hypothesis `H` gives us `N ∈ D` such that `B N hN ≠ {N}`, so `B N hN` must contain at least two non-zero independent submodules. \n- Since `N ∈ D` but `N` is not in `D'` (unless `B N hN = {N}`), we might exploit this to show `D' ≠ D`. But this isn't directly correct because `sSup (B N hN) = N` does not imply `N` is in `B N hN`. \n   - In fact, `B N hN` can be a collection of proper submodules whose sSup is `N`, e.g., a direct sum decomposition of `N` into smaller submodules. \n   - The problem is that `D'` is defined to include all the submodules in all `B N hN`, and we would have `sSup D' = ⊤`, but `D'` could potentially cover all of `D` already if every element of `D` is decomposed into smaller pieces that are already in `D'`. So, `D'` can potentially equal `D`.\n\nHowever, in the current setup, we are missing a crucial ingredient: the refinement is supposed to replace each `N ∈ D` with a set of smaller submodules. The current `hB` says `N = sSup (B N hN)`, but `hB'` only requires `B N hN` to be `sSupIndep`, but not necessarily a direct sum decomposition into proper submodules. For example, `B N hN = {N}` is allowed because `sSup {N} = N` and `{N}` is `sSupIndep` (since there's only one element). \n\nBut `H` says that for *some* `N`, `B N hN ≠ {N}`. That means `B N hN` actually contains more than one element. \n\nIn fact, since `sSupIndep (B N hN)` is not empty (because of `sSup (B N hN) = N`, so if `B N hN` was empty, `sSup ∅ = ⊥ < N